Bring a #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{0.5%tsp}.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nests{2} and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} or #wok{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{260%g} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fry, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.
> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Meanwhile, halve the @plums{2}, remove the stones and chop each half into three wedges.

Trim the @pak choi{1}, then thinly slice widthways.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Lower the heat to medium and add the plums and @sugar{1} to the chicken.

Stir-fry until the plums start to colour, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @ginger puree{7.5%g} and as many @chilli flakes{1} as you'd like (careful, they're hot).

Stir-fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the pak choi and stir-fry until just soft, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @hoisin sauce{32%g}, @ketjap manis{25%g} and @water{2%tbsp}, ensuring everything's well coated.

Add the cooked noodles to the pan. Stir together and cook until everything's piping hot and combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Share the chicken and plum stir-fry between your #bowls{}.

Scatter over the @salted peanuts{25%g} to finish.

Enjoy!